      VULNERABILITY DETAILS<b class="line"><!---->VULNERABILITY DETAILS<!----></b><br>use-of-uninitialized-value when av1 decoder try to decode the crafted files.<span class="line"><!---->use-of-uninitialized-value when av1 decoder try to decode the crafted files.<!----></span><br><br>VERSION<b class="line"><!---->VERSION<!----></b><br>Chrome Version:<span class="line"><!---->Chrome Version:<!----></span><br>Operating System: Linux<span class="line"><!---->Operating System: Linux<!----></span><br><br>REPRODUCTION CASE<b class="line"><!---->REPRODUCTION CASE<!----></b><br><br>To build the memory sanitize version of libaom with debug info:<span class="line"><!---->To build the memory sanitize version of libaom with debug info:<!----></span><br>1. git clone <span class="line"><!---->1. git clone <!----></span>https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/"><!---->https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/<!----></a><br>2. Set the compiler environment to clang and suppose we are in the source root of the libaom:<span class="line"><!---->2. Set the compiler environment to clang and suppose we are in the source root of the libaom:<!----></span><br>mkdir build && cd build<span class="line"><!---->mkdir build &amp;&amp; cd build<!----></span><br>cmake ../ -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=x86_64 -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=DEBUG -DCONFIG_PIC=1 -DCONFIG_SCALABILITY=0 -DFORCE_HIGHBITDEPTH_DECODING=0 -DCONFIG_LIBYUV=0 -DCONFIG_AV1_ENCODER=0 -DENABLE_EXAMPLES=1 -DENABLE_DOCS=0 -DENABLE_TESTS=0 -DCONFIG_SIZE_LIMIT=1 -DDECODE_HEIGHT_LIMIT=12288 -DDECODE_WIDTH_LIMIT=12288 -DSANITIZE=memory -DAOM_EXTRA_C_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824" -DAOM_EXTRA_CXX_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824"<span class="line"><!---->cmake ../ -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=x86_64 -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=DEBUG -DCONFIG_PIC=1 -DCONFIG_SCALABILITY=0 -DFORCE_HIGHBITDEPTH_DECODING=0 -DCONFIG_LIBYUV=0 -DCONFIG_AV1_ENCODER=0 -DENABLE_EXAMPLES=1 -DENABLE_DOCS=0 -DENABLE_TESTS=0 -DCONFIG_SIZE_LIMIT=1 -DDECODE_HEIGHT_LIMIT=12288 -DDECODE_WIDTH_LIMIT=12288 -DSANITIZE=memory -DAOM_EXTRA_C_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824" -DAOM_EXTRA_CXX_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824"<!----></span><br><br>3. make simple_decoder -j$(nproc)<span class="line"><!---->3. make simple_decoder -j$(nproc)<!----></span><br>4. the simple_decoder will located at examples/simple_decoder, and try to run it with the attached file:<span class="line"><!---->4. the simple_decoder will located at examples/simple_decoder, and try to run it with the attached file:<!----></span><br><br>./simple_decoder use-of-uninitialized-tile.ivf tmp_out<span class="line"><!---->./simple_decoder use-of-uninitialized-tile.ivf tmp_out<!----></span><br><br><br><br>FOR CRASHES, PLEASE INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING ADDITIONAL INFORMATION<b class="line"><!---->FOR CRASHES, PLEASE INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING ADDITIONAL         The comment in <span class="line"><!---->The comment in <!----></span>https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6"><!---->https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6<!----></a> applies here too.<span class="line"><!----> applies here too.<!----></span><br><br>Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<span class="line"><!---->Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<!----></span><br><br>I updated the affected platforms based on where libaom is enabled [1]<span class="line"><!---->I updated the affected platforms based on where libaom is enabled [1]<!----></span><br><br>[1] <span class="line"><!---->[1] <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b<!----></a><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

          <a class="comment-link" href="?id=1212902#c9">Comment 9<!----></a>

          
        by
        <mr-user-link></mr-user-link>

        <chops-timestamp title="Thu, May 27, 2021, 3:28 PM EDT"></chops-timestamp>
        
          <span class="role-label">Project Member</span>

      <div role="heading" class="comment-header" aria-level="2">
        <div>
          <a class="comment-link" href="?id=1212902#c9">Comment 9<!----></a>

          
        by
        <mr-user-link></mr-user-link>
        on
        <chops-timestamp title="Thu, May 27, 2021, 3:28 PM EDT"></chops-timestamp>
        
          <span class="role-label">Project Member</span>
      
        </div>
        
      </div>
    
      
        
        
      
        Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<span class="line"><!---->Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<!----></span><br><br>I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<span class="line"><!---->I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        
          
        <div>
          
        </div>
      <div class="comment-body">
        <mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        <div>
          
        </div>
      </div>

          Comment 10<a class="comment-link" href="?id=1212902#c10">Comment 10<!----></a>

        Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<span class="line"><!---->Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<span class="line"><!---->Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly.         Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<span class="line"><!---->Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<!----></span><br><br>I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<span class="line"><!---->I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        
          
        <div>
          
        </div>

        <mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

      </div><br>
    
        
      
        Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<span class="line"><!---->Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

            Reported by

        <div class="main-text">
          <h1>

          </h1>

      VULNERABILITY DETAILS<b class="line"><!---->VULNERABILITY DETAILS<!----></b><br>use-of-uninitialized-value when av1 decoder try to decode the crafted files.<span class="line"><!---->use-of-uninitialized-value when av1 decoder try to decode the crafted files.<!----></span><br><br>VERSION<b class="line"><!---->VERSION<!----></b><br>Chrome Version:<span class="line"><!---->Chrome Version:<!----></span><br>Operating System: Linux<span class="line"><!---->Operating System: Linux<!----></span><br><br>REPRODUCTION CASE<b class="line"><!---->REPRODUCTION CASE<!----></b><br><br>To build the memory sanitize version of libaom with debug info:<span class="line"><!---->To build the memory sanitize version of libaom with debug info:<!----></span><br>1. git clone <span class="line"><!---->1. git clone <!----></span>https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/"><!---->https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/<!----></a><br>2. Set the compiler environment to clang and suppose we are in the source root of the libaom:<span class="line"><!---->2. Set the compiler environment to clang and suppose we are in the source root of the libaom:<!----></span><br>mkdir build && cd build<span class="line"><!---->mkdir build &amp;&amp; cd build<!----></span><br>cmake ../ -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=x86_64 -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=DEBUG -DCONFIG_PIC=1 -DCONFIG_SCALABILITY=0 -DFORCE_HIGHBITDEPTH_DECODING=0 -DCONFIG_LIBYUV=0 -DCONFIG_AV1_ENCODER=0 -DENABLE_EXAMPLES=1 -DENABLE_DOCS=0 -DENABLE_TESTS=0 -DCONFIG_SIZE_LIMIT=1 -DDECODE_HEIGHT_LIMIT=12288 -DDECODE_WIDTH_LIMIT=12288 -DSANITIZE=memory -DAOM_EXTRA_C_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824" -DAOM_EXTRA_CXX_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824"<span class="line"><!---->cmake ../ -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=x86_64 -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=DEBUG -DCONFIG_PIC=1 -DCONFIG_SCALABILITY=0 -DFORCE_HIGHBITDEPTH_DECODING=0 -DCONFIG_LIBYUV=0 -DCONFIG_AV1_ENCODER=0 -DENABLE_EXAMPLES=1 -DENABLE_DOCS=0 -DENABLE_TESTS=0 -DCONFIG_SIZE_LIMIT=1 -DDECODE_HEIGHT_LIMIT=12288 -DDECODE_WIDTH_LIMIT=12288 -DSANITIZE=memory -DAOM_EXTRA_C_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824" -DAOM_EXTRA_CXX_FLAGS="-g -DAOM_MAX_ALLOCABLE_MEMORY=1073741824"<!----></span><br><br>3. make simple_decoder -j$(nproc)<span class="line"><!---->3. make simple_decoder -j$(nproc)<!----></span><br>4. the simple_decoder will located at examples/simple_decoder, and try to run it with the attached file:<span class="line"><!---->4. the simple_decoder will located at examples/simple_decoder, and try to run it with the attached file:<!----></span><br><br>./simple_decoder use-of-uninitialized-tile.ivf tmp_out<span class="line"><!---->./simple_decoder use-of-uninitialized-tile.ivf tmp_out<!----></span><br><br><br><br>FOR CRASHES, PLEASE INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING ADDITIONAL INFORMATION<b class="line"><!---->FOR CRASHES, PLEASE INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING ADDITIONAL INFORMATION<!----></b><br>Type of crash: <span class="line"><!---->Type of crash: <!----></span><br>Crash State: <span class="line"><!---->Crash State: <!----></span><br><br>The crash trace:<span This file may not decode properly.Using AOMedia Project AV1 Decoder 3.1.0-243-g87682566c<span class="line"><!---->Error: Unrecognized IVF version!           <a class="comment-link" href="?id=1212902#c8">Comment 8<!----></a>

          
        by
        <mr-user-link></mr-user-link>
        on

          Labels:<strong><!---->Labels:</strong>
          
          -OS-Android -OS-Fuchsia
          
          <br>
        
        
      <div class="issue-diff">
        <!---->
          <strong><!---->Labels:</strong>
          
          -OS-Android -OS-Fuchsia
          
          <br>
        <!---->
        
      </div><br>
    
        
      
        The comment in <span class="line"><!---->The comment in <!----></span>https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6"><!---->https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6<!----></a> applies here too.<span class="line"><!----> applies here too.<!----></span><br><br>Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<span class="line"><!---->Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<!----></span><br><br>I updated the affected platforms based on where libaom is enabled [1]<span class="line"><!---->I updated the affected platforms based on where libaom is enabled [1]<!----></span><br><br>[1] <span class="line"><!---->[1] <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b<!----></a><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<span class="line"><!---->Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<!----></span><br><br>I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<span class="line"><!---->I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        
          
        <div>
          
        </div>

        Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<span class="line"><!---->Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        The comment in <span class="line"><!---->The comment in <!----></span>https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6"><!---->https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1213030#c6<!----></a> applies here too.<span class="line"><!----> applies here too.<!----></span><br><br>Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<span class="line"><!---->Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<!----></span><br><br>I updated the affected platforms based on where libaom is enabled [1]<span class="line"><!---->I updated the affected platforms based on where libaom is enabled [1]<!----></span><br><br>[1] <span class="line"><!---->[1] <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/libaom/options.gni;drc=e717d8d14853021772a65c1de7b7a630c7342f7b<!----></a><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        by

        Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<span class="line"><!---->Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<!----></span><br><br>I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<span class="line"><!---->I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        
          
        <div>
          
        </div>

        Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<span class="line"><!---->Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

      VULNERABILITY DETAILS<b class="line"><!---->VULNERABILITY DETAILS<!----></b><br>use-of-uninitialized-value when av1 decoder try to decode the crafted files.<span class="line"><!---->use-of-uninitialized-value when av1 decoder try to decode the crafted files.<!----></span><br><br>VERSION<b class="line"><!---->VERSION<!----></b><br>Chrome Version:<span class="line"><!---->Chrome Version:<!----></span><br>Operating System: Linux<span class="line"><!---->Operating System: Linux<!----></span><br><br>REPRODUCTION CASE<b class="line"><!---->REPRODUCTION CASE<!----></b><br><br>To build the memory sanitize version of libaom with debug info:<span class="line"><!---->To build the memory sanitize version of libaom with debug info:<!----></span><br>1. git clone <span class="line"><!---->1. git clone <!----></span>https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/"><!---->https://aomedia.googlesource.com/aom/<!----></a><br>2. Set the compiler environment to clang and suppose we are in the source root of the libaom:<span class="line"><!---->2. That doesn't appear to be the case here, but libaom does have some so we most likely won't want to enable this configuration in ClusterFuzz (elsewhere we test with AOM_TARGET_CPU=generic to run through C-code only).<span class="line"><!---->Using memory sanitizer with a x86 build with micro-architecture optimizations enabled (avx2, etc) can lead to false positives when the code uses handwritten assembly.         Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<span class="line"><!---->Another thing I forgot to mention in regards to memory sanitizer and the assembly (hand rolled or compiler intrinsics) is often the code will over read/write within bounds to a buffer the decoder owns, but leave values that aren't part of the reconstructed frame uninitialized. valgrind is usually a better way to detect whether the values are used meaningfully. MSan avoids this due to the overhead involved.<!----></span><br><br>I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<span class="line"><!---->I can reproduce this with aomdec/simple_decoder at v3.1.0-268-g7aab8e15f using MSan, but valgrind doesn't report an issue. I'll take a closer look using the fuzzer and inspecting the reconstructed frame if the decoder produces one, but my first thought is we're dealing with the case above so it would be NSI.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        
          
        <div>
          
        </div>

        Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<span class="line"><!---->Setting -DAOM_TARGET_CPU=generic doesn't report any issues with this file. We could mitigate some of the MSan warnings in the intrinsics as we've done in projects that only use them, but until the library removes the hand rolled assembly this won't be a valid configuration. valgrind is a better way to check the impact of the fuzzed data in this case.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        /*
         * Really specific class names are necessary because ShadowDOM
         * is disabled for this component.
         */
        .chops-autocomplete-container {
          position: relative;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container table {
          padding: 0;
          font-size: var(--chops-main-font-size);
          color: var(--chops-link-color);
          position: absolute;
          background: var(--chops-white);
          border: var(--chops-accessible-border);
          z-index: 999;
          box-shadow: 2px 3px 8px 0px hsla(0, 0%, 0%, 0.3);
          border-spacing: 0;
          border-collapse: collapse;
          /* In the case when the autocomplete extends the
           * height of the viewport, we want to make sure
           * there's spacing. */
          margin-bottom: 1em;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container tbody {
          display: block;
          min-width: 100px;
          max-height: 500px;
          overflow: auto;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container tr {
          cursor: pointer;
          transition: background 0.2s ease-in-out;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container tr[data-selected] {
          background: var(--chops-active-choice-bg);
          text-decoration: underline;

 runOnLoad(function() {
 if (typeof(ClientLogger) === "function") {
 let cl = new ClientLogger("issues");
 if (cl.started("new-issue")) {
 cl.logEnd("new-issue", null, 120 * 1000);
 }
 if (cl.started("issue-search")) {
 cl.logEnd("issue-search");
 }
 }
 });
